      "side": 1,
      "message": "\u003e the interfaces they expose are actually quite simple\n\nI think it is bold claim. As a user of this func, I have to read\n\n  export function buildContextProviderMixin\u003cCtx\u003e(providedContexts: Array\u003ckeyof Ctx\u003e) {\n    return function providerMixin\u003cT extends LitElement \u0026 Ctx, C extends Constructor\u003cT\u003e\u003e(cls: C) {\n\nand this hurts my eyes to be honest. If I was coming from a JS world, this would be a lot to take in compared to a version without type parameterization. \n\nThe type systems in C# and TypeScript (the same language designer, Anders Hejlsberg) tempt the engineer to write a perfect type expression like the one above, but it comes with cost of readability/maintainability (and I bet you spend some time coming up with these expressions). I generally recommend to keep things simple; simplicity goes a long way; managing complexity is the most important thing in software engineering. It is not obvious to me that this cost/benefit balance is done well here.",
